# shadcn instructions

Use the latest version of Shadcn to install new components, like this command to add a button component:

```bash
pnpm dlx shadcn@latest add button
```

When a new requirement or feature needs a missing UI primitive, install the exact shadcn component immediately before implementing UI:

```bash
pnpm dlx shadcn@latest add <component-name>
```

Shadcn usage rules:
- Prefer shadcn components over custom raw UI for forms, overlays, navigation, tables, and feedback states
- Build feature UIs by composing shadcn primitives inside feature components
- Keep custom wrappers thin and feature-oriented (do not fork shadcn internals unless required)
- If multiple components are needed, install all required components in one command
- Keep component variants consistent with project warm theme tokens in `src/styles.css`

# commit message instructions

When generating git commit messages, follow Conventional Commit format and include a descriptive body.

Required format:

```text
<type>(<optional-scope>): <short summary>

<why this change is needed and what problem it solves>

<optional bullet list for key changes>
```

Rules:
- Use one of: feat, fix, docs, style, refactor, perf, test, build, ci, chore, revert
- Keep subject line concise and imperative (about 50-72 chars when possible)
- Always include a body with context (not only a one-line subject)
- Prefer explaining "why" and impact, not just file-level "what"
- Never add `Co-authored-by`, `Made-with`, or any vendor/tool attribution to commits or PRs
- Never use `git commit --trailer`; write the full message in `-m` / HEREDOC only

# react + tanstack engineering rules

Stack assumptions for this repository:
- TanStack Start + TanStack Router + TanStack Query + React + TypeScript
- Server/client boundaries must stay explicit and type-safe

Core implementation rules:
- Use function components and named exports
- Keep components focused; move data logic into hooks/services
- Prefer route-level loaders and query prefetching for initial data
- Use TanStack Query for remote async state; avoid duplicating server state in local state
- Use search params for shareable filter/sort/pagination state
- Co-locate route files with their UI and data dependencies
- Validate all external input (URL params, forms, server functions) with zod
- Use optimistic updates only when rollback is clearly implemented
- Invalidate query keys intentionally after mutations (do not invalidate everything)
- Keep query keys centralized and deterministic
- Handle loading/error/empty/success states explicitly in UI

Server/client boundary rules:
- Put DB calls and secret-dependent logic in server-only modules
- Never expose secrets to client code (`VITE_` vars are public)
- Keep server functions small and composable
- Return typed DTOs from server functions; avoid leaking DB internals

Refactor rules:
- Prefer small, isolated refactors per concern (UI, query, schema, routing)
- Preserve behavior first; refactor with tests or type checks passing
- Remove duplication by extracting pure helpers/hooks, not by creating deep abstractions
- Keep files under ~250 lines when practical; split by responsibility when they grow
- Avoid broad rewrites unless explicitly requested

# domain-driven folder structure (money diary)

Use feature folders in `src/features`:

```text
src/
  features/
    transactions/   # money in/out entries
    savings/        # current savings, savings ledger, transfers to savings
    wishlist/       # things user wants to buy
    goals/          # financial goals (distinct from wishlist)
    categories/     # game, netflix, ai-subscription, etc.
    analytics/      # spending trends and category/title insights
```

Per-feature module shape:
- `api/` server functions and data access adapters
- `components/` feature UI components
- `hooks/` feature hooks (query/mutation orchestration)
- `schemas/` zod schemas and parsing
- `types/` feature interfaces
- `utils/` pure helpers

Routing guidance:
- `src/routes/transactions/*`
- `src/routes/savings/*`
- `src/routes/wishlist/*`
- `src/routes/goals/*`
- `src/routes/analytics/*`

Money Diary business entities:
- Transaction: amount, type (`income` | `expense` | `transfer`), title, category, date, notes, source
- SavingsEntry: amount, sourceTransactionId, date, note
- WishlistItem: title, targetAmount, priority, status
- FinancialGoal: title, targetAmount, targetDate, status, progress
- Category: name, slug, kind (`need` | `want` | `subscription` | `other`)

Product behavior expectations:
- User can log income and expense entries
- User can mark what portion of income moved into savings
- Wishlist is separate from financial goals
- Dashboard can show: current savings, current expenditure, top spending categories/titles
- Analytics supports filtering by date range, category, and title

Code quality gates for generated changes:
- Add/update zod schema for any new input surface
- Add/update query keys for new server data dependencies
- Add/update route loader dependencies when data is required at navigation time
- Keep empty/error states present in UI screens

# api-first delivery rules

Implementation order for each feature:
1. Define/update DB schema
2. Build API/server routes + validation
3. Update OpenAPI (`/api/openapi/json`)
4. Build UI pages that consume the API

API rules:
- Do not create feature pages before corresponding API endpoints exist
- Every new API endpoint must be documented in OpenAPI in the same change
- Use zod validation for request payloads and query params
- Return consistent JSON shape for success and error responses

# release version and changelog

`src/content/changelog.ts` is shown to **end users** in Settings → About and in the update prompt. Write for people using Money Diary to manage money — not for you as the developer.

## When to bump version + add a changelog entry

Only when the change is **user-visible** (new capability, UX improvement, or bug fix they would notice).

Skip version/changelog for internal-only work: analytics, tracking, admin tooling, infra, refactors, dependency updates, or ops changes users never see.

Deploy-only changes still ship via `VITE_APP_BUILD_ID`; users may get an update prompt without a new changelog line.

## How to write entries

- Focus on **what users can do** or **what got better/fixed** in plain language
- Good: "Reply to support tickets in Settings", "Faster transaction list on mobile"
- Bad: "Added Vercel Speed Insights", "Removed admin online count", "Pusher presence channel", "OpenAPI updated"

Do **not** mention: admin panels, monitoring, tracking, Pusher, APIs, migrations, or implementation details.

## Checklist (user-facing ships only)

1. Bump `APP_VERSION` in `src/lib/app-version.ts` (patch for small fixes/features, minor for larger releases)
2. Add a new entry at the top of `CHANGELOG_RELEASES` in `src/content/changelog.ts` (version, date, title, highlights)
3. Keep `src/routes/api/openapi.json.ts` `info.version` in sync with `APP_VERSION`
4. Include the version bump in the same PR as the feature work
